T1  - The Liminality of Trajectory Shifts in Institutional Entrepreneurship
AU  - Henfridsson, Ola
AU  - Yoo, Youngjin
Y1  - 2013/12/23
PY  - 2013
DA  - 2014/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/orsc.2013.0883
DO  - 10.1287/orsc.2013.0883
T2  - Organization Science
JF  - Organization Science
JO  - Organization Science
SP  - 932
EP  - 950
VL  - 25
IS  - 3
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - In this paper, we develop a process model of trajectory shifts in institutional entrepreneurship. We focus on the liminal periods experienced by institutional entrepreneurs when they, unlike the rest of the organization, recognize limits in the present and seek to shift a familiar past into an unfamiliar and uncertain future. Such periods involve a situation where the new possible future, not yet fully formed, exists side-by-side with established innovation trajectories. Trajectory shifts are moments of truth for institutional entrepreneurs, but little is known about the underlying mechanisms of how entrepreneurs reflectively deal with liminality to conceive and bring forth new innovation trajectories. Our in-depth case study research at CarCorp traces three such mechanisms (reflective dissension, imaginative projection, and eliminatory exploration) and builds the basis for understanding the liminality of trajectory shifts. The paper offers theoretical implications for the institutional entrepreneurship literature.
